[30;1m884 | [0m[35m<h3>Context managers<a class="headerlink" href="#context-managers" title="Permalink to this heading"[0m
[30;1m885 | [0m[35m<p>The database object itself can be used as a context-manager, which opens a[0m
[30;1m886 | [0m[35mconnection for the duration of the wrapped block of code. Additionally, a[0m
[30;1m887 | [0m[35mtransaction is opened at the start of the wrapped block and committed before[0m
[30;1m888 | [0m[35mthe connection is closed (unless an error occurs, in which case the transaction[0m
[30;1m889 | [0m[35mis rolled back).</p>[0m

[30;1m957 | [0m[35mWhen psycopg2 executes a query, normally all results are fetched and returned[0m
[30;1m958 | [0m[35mto the client by the backend. This can cause your application to use a lot of[0m
[30;1m959 | [0m[35mmemory when making large queries. Using server-side cursors, results are[0m
[30;1m960 | [0m[35mreturned a little at a time (by default 2000 records). For the definitive[0m
[30;1m961 | [0m[35mreference, please see the `psycopg2 documentation <http://initd.org/psycopg/docs/usage.html#server-s[0m
[30;1m962 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m963 | [0m[35m.. note:: To use server-side (or named) cursors, you must be using :py:class:`PostgresqlExtDatabase`[0m

[30;1m574 | [0m[35mSQLite uses dynamic typing and data-types are not enforced, it can be perfectly[0m
[30;1m575 | [0m[35mfine to declare fields without *any* data-type. In those cases you can use[0m
[30;1m576 | [0m[35m:py:class:`BareField`. It is also common for SQLite virtual tables to use[0m
[30;1m577 | [0m[35mmeta-columns or untyped columns, so for those cases as well you may wish to use[0m
[30;1m578 | [0m[35man untyped field (although for full-text search, you should use[0m

[30;1m163 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m164 | [0m[35mPreviously, Peewee emulated autocommit behavior for top-level queries issued[0m
[30;1m165 | [0m[35moutside of a transaction. This necessitated a number of checks which had to be[0m
[30;1m166 | [0m[35mperformed each time a query was executed, so as to ensure that we didn't end up[0m
[30;1m167 | [0m[35mwith uncommitted writes or, conversely, idle read transactions. By running the[0m
[30;1m168 | [0m[35munderlying driver in autocommit mode, we can eliminate all these checks, since[0m
[30;1m169 | [0m[35mwe are already managing transactions ourselves.[0m

[30;1m1445 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m1446 | [0m[35mLet's look at another example. In this example we will calculate the "opposite"[0m
[30;1m1447 | [0m[35mof a running total, in which the total sum of all values is decreased by the[0m
[30;1m1448 | [0m[35mvalue of the samples, ordered by ``id``. To accomplish this, we'll calculate[0m
[30;1m1449 | [0m[35mthe sum from the current row to the last row.[0m

[30;1m521 | [0m[35m* ``EXCLUDED``: this "magic" namespace allows you to reference the new data[0m

[30;1m22 | [0m[35mread time, we see what version the row is currently at, and on save, we ensure[0m

[30;1m21 | [0m[35minstead rely on an internal *version* column in the row we're modifying. At[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35mread time, we see what version the row is currently at, and on save, we ensure[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35mthat the update takes place only if the version is the same as the one we[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35minitially read. If the version is higher, then some other process must have[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35msnuck in and changed the row -- to save our modified version could result in[0m

[30;1m954 | [0m[35mThis situation is similar to the previous example, but there is one important[0m
[30;1m955 | [0m[35mdifference: when we selected tweets, they only have a single associated user,[0m
[30;1m956 | [0m[35mso we could directly assign the foreign key. The reverse is not true, however,[0m

[30;1m889 | [0m[35m------------------------[0m
[30;1m890 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m891 | [0m[35mThe *N+1 problem* refers to a situation where an application performs a query,[0m
[30;1m892 | [0m[35mthen for each row of the result set, the application performs at least one[0m
[30;1m893 | [0m[35mother query (another way to conceptualize this is as a nested loop). In many[0m
[30;1m894 | [0m[35mcases, these *n* queries can be avoided through the use of a SQL join or[0m
[30;1m895 | [0m[35msubquery. The database itself may do a nested loop, but it will usually be more[0m

[30;1m1003 | [0m[35mSome things to consider when using :py:func:`prefetch`:[0m
[30;1m1004 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m1005 | [0m[35m* Foreign keys must exist between the models being prefetched.[0m
[30;1m1006 | [0m[35m* `LIMIT` works as you'd expect on the outer-most query, but may be difficult[0m
[30;1m1007 | [0m[35m  to implement correctly if trying to limit the size of the sub-selects.[0m
[30;1m1008 | [0m[35m  * The parameter `prefetch_type` may be used when `LIMIT` is not supported[0m
[30;1m1009 | [0m[35m    with the default query construction (e.g. with MySQL).[0m

[30;1m2600 | [0m[35m            When a ``FROM`` clause is present, what essentially happens is that[0m
[30;1m2601 | [0m[35m            the target table is joined to the tables mentioned in the[0m
[30;1m2602 | [0m[35m            from_list, and each output row of the join represents an update[0m
[30;1m2603 | [0m[35m            operation for the target table. When using ``FROM`` you should[0m
[30;1m2604 | [0m[35m            ensure that the join produces at most one output row for each row[0m
[30;1m2605 | [0m[35m            to be modified.[0m
[30;1m2606 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m131 | [0m[35mfunctionality and improved performance for SQLite database users. Peewee will[0m
[30;1m132 | [0m[35mattempt to determine ahead-of-time if SQLite3 is installed, and only build the[0m
[30;1m133 | [0m[35mSQLite extensions if the SQLite shared-library is available on your system.</p>[0m
[30;1m134 | [0m[35m<p>If, however, you receive errors like the following when attempting to install[0m
[30;1m135 | [0m[35mPeewee, you can explicitly disable the compilation of the SQLite C extensions[0m

[30;1m837 | [0m[35m<section id="avoiding-the-n-1-problem">[0m
[30;1m838 | [0m[35m<span id="nplusone"></span><h2>Avoiding the N+1 problem<a class="headerlink" href="#avoiding-the-n-1[0m
[30;1m839 | [0m[35m<p>The <em>N+1 problem</em> refers to a situation where an application performs a query,[0m
[30;1m840 | [0m[35mthen for each row of the result set, the application performs at least one[0m
[30;1m841 | [0m[35mother query (another way to conceptualize this is as a nested loop). In many[0m
[30;1m842 | [0m[35mcases, these <em>n</em> queries can be avoided through the use of a SQL join or[0m
[30;1m843 | [0m[35msubquery. The database itself may do a nested loop, but it will usually be more[0m

[30;1m82 | [0m[35mNow that we have our models, let's connect to the database. Although it's not[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mnecessary to open the connection explicitly, it is good practice since it will[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mreveal any errors with your database connection immediately, as opposed to some[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35marbitrary time later when the first query is executed. It is also good to close[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35mthe connection when you are done -- for instance, a web app might open a[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35mconnection when it receives a request, and close the connection when it sends[0m
